{"key":"post-10045908","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10045908</id>\n<content>The foil needs to be there.&amp;nbsp; Make sure you're using squares of foil that only protect the cake from trying to colonize the perlite.&amp;nbsp; Don't let the foil cover the whole surface.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Another tip is to use your fingers to 'rake' the perlite so it has lots of ridges and an irregular surface.&amp;nbsp; This greatly increases the surface area, giving more humidity.&amp;nbsp; Also make sure when you mist that the overspray covers the perlite, re-moistening it.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;For now, pile a tablespoon or so of vermiculte on each cake and soak it well.&amp;nbsp; This will hydrate your cakes from the top down and supply water for the current flush.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10046575</next>\n<prev>10045671</prev>\n<first>10007638</first>\n<last>10046795</last>\n<when>1238094728</when>\n<utime>03/26/09 10:12 PM</utime>\n</post>"}